1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,775
We can look at math from two

2
00:00:01,875 --> 00:00:05,594
different points of view. Syntactically and Semantically.

3
00:00:05,666 --> 00:00:09,001
The world of syntax is a formal and mechanical world

4
00:00:09,101 --> 00:00:12,436
where truth is given by proofs in a formal calculus.

5
00:00:12,533 --> 00:00:15,750
Which is just a specific set of axioms

6
00:00:15,866 --> 00:00:18,782
written in a formal language, which can be combined

7
00:00:18,882 --> 00:00:22,271
according to certain rules of inference to generate proofs.

8
00:00:22,933 --> 00:00:26,789
The semantics is the intuitive world in which the symbols

9
00:00:26,889 --> 00:00:30,954
of our logical language get interpreted into. Similar to how

10
00:00:31,054 --> 00:00:35,396
English words are just words which describe things that actually

11
00:00:35,496 --> 00:00:39,144
exist in the world. If viewed platonically, we can see

12
00:00:39,244 --> 00:00:45,183
mathematical formulas as describing properties of pre-existing structures which enhabit

13
00:00:45,283 --> 00:00:46,918
a perfect world of forms.

14
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:50,320
This platonistic view of math is not shared by everyone. Some hold

15
00:00:50,420 --> 00:00:53,792
a formalist view of math, in which they essentially just ignore the

16
00:00:53,892 --> 00:00:57,471
semantic side of math. Others hold a constructivist view of math, where

17
00:00:57,571 --> 00:01:00,166
we have to be able to construct or at least define a

18
00:01:00,266 --> 00:01:02,913
mathematical object before we can say that it exists.

19
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:06,380
But the branch of mathematics which deals with the relation

20
00:01:06,480 --> 00:01:10,038
between the syntax and the semantics --known as Model Theory--

21
00:01:10,138 --> 00:01:13,401
makes the most sense when viewed from the platonic world.

22
00:01:14,466 --> 00:01:18,375
In model theory, mathematical formulas aquire meaning

23
00:01:18,475 --> 00:01:21,628
when they get interpreted into a structure.

24
00:01:21,666 --> 00:01:24,544
So 1 plus 1 equals 2,

25
00:01:24,600 --> 00:01:26,837
gets its meaning only when we interpret each

26
00:01:26,937 --> 00:01:29,228
of the symbols involved into the number line.

27
00:01:29,266 --> 00:01:35,070
First draw an arrow from 2 to the number 2 on the number line,

28
00:01:35,133 --> 00:01:37,974
then draw an arrow from plus into a square box with

29
00:01:38,074 --> 00:01:41,145
two input lines, and one output line, with plus inside.

30
00:01:41,266 --> 00:01:45,659
Then draw arrows from the 1's in the formula to the input wires,

31
00:01:45,733 --> 00:01:52,766
and then draw an arrow from the output wire

32
00:01:52,866 --> 00:01:58,407
to the point 2 on the number line.

33
00:01:58,466 --> 00:02:01,893
We will make this precise in the next two videos.

34
00:02:02,933 --> 00:02:07,065
There are different languages within which we can define our logic:

35
00:02:07,133 --> 00:02:10,089
Propositional or 0th order logic,

36
00:02:10,133 --> 00:02:12,149
FOL

37
00:02:12,200 --> 00:02:15,809
and finally Higher OL's.

38
00:02:15,866 --> 00:02:19,512
Of these FOL is used to build or define mathematics. This

39
00:02:19,612 --> 00:02:24,243
is because FOL is strong enough to describe most mathematical structures

40
00:02:24,343 --> 00:02:27,660
well enough, and not so strong that we can no longer

41
00:02:27,760 --> 00:02:30,551
define a complete and sound calculus for it.

42
00:02:30,600 --> 00:02:34,250
So propositional logic is too weak for our purposes, and

43
00:02:34,350 --> 00:02:37,331
SOL is so strong that we lost control over it.

44
00:02:37,431 --> 00:02:40,478
We will see what this means later in the video.

45
00:02:40,533 --> 00:02:42,422
But, we will start simple by

46
00:02:42,522 --> 00:02:45,762
understanding the basic of propositional logic.

